@node introduction "Description"
@toc main

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

Ever wondered what the public name of a particular public screen was? Well, fear no more! PubScreenList is here! PubScreenList will print for you all the names of public screens it finds.
@endnode
@node installation "Installation"
@toc main

@{b}Installation@{ub}

Copy the program to any directory you like.
@endnode
@node usage "Usage"
@toc main

@{b}Usage@{ub}

Run the program from within a shell. You will see entries like this:

node = $002F472C    visitors = 5      screen = $002F48A8    name = Workbench

node     - The address where the PubScreenNode was located;
visitors  - The number of windows and requesters using the screen;
screen   - The address of the screen itself;
name     - The public name of the screen.

You can use the public name in any program that can open on a named public screen.
@endnode
